totally consumed by crowd control duties.<br>
<br>
1)  If you're short on shaman power, for Tunare's sake, SLOW!  If you have a shaman, and they're having trouble landing when the mob is tashed/malosi'd (they are lower level than the mob/you), don't hesitate - even the fast and cheap Tepid Deeds (50% slow) is MUCH better than watching your melees get shredded.<br>
Keep this spell in your lineup unless you are absolutely SURE you won't need it.  If you're the backup chanter there's no reason you can't fit this in, and you should have a strip/pillage enchantment loaded as well, your main CC is most likely going to be too busy to handle this.<br>
<br>
2)  If your shaman or you know you are going to have trouble landing on a particularly hard hitting mob,  - Tash as soon as humanly possible (as soon as the MT has gotten a couple of rounds in).  Taking the tash agro can suck, and be fatal, but against large mobs the death of your MT due to lack of debuffing is much, much worse.  If it's mainly your nukers complaining about difficulty landing, the tash can wait a few rounds.<br>
<br>
3) A great tip (courtesy of someone, I don't remember who, from Lost Fires) regarding chain-runing:<br>
Hopefully, you're going to be chain-runing only your MT.  But often, you're a fair distance from that sort of fight, the MT dies, and if you're unlucky the ST dies.  Agro has fallen upon a backup pally or SK, or more likely some poor squishy monk rogue or ranger who is doing too much damage for their own good.  What do you do?  Make a hotkey /assisting the offending mob (erm, do this *before* the fight), and Rune whomever he's wailing on.  Voila, you've become a backup cleric.  But be sure you spell the monster's name right <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .<br>
<br>
4) Stripping of buffs (done by you):  Two things here.  1) If mobs have a DS or other buffs on them, and it's not absolutely *critical* that that mob get slowed IMMEDIATELY, yank those suckers off!  Classes who use fast weapons can get eaten alive by even small damage shields, and the amount of damage they can do to an entire raiding party is huge, straining healer resources.  2) This spell line can be invaluable if, god forbid, your MT gets charmed (happens fairly often in mid-level encounters) or someone gets a really horrendous DoT.  If this happens, ignore the crying about their lost haste (you're going to have to do it again soon anyway) - get that party member back to working for the team!  If this is a chronic problem, use a junk buff as the first buff, and then have the party remove it, thus making sure the buff you strip is the 'problem' one.<br>
<br>
Stripping of buffs (done by mobs):  This is a major pain in the butt.  What can you do?  Ideally, you should be stunlocking them, but resists happen, and you may not be able to get to the offending creature(s) right away.<br>
Junk Junk Junk!!  Carry stacks of fish scales for EB if you have to, other classes (druids and shamen are especially good for junking) can help with this.  Passing out a round of See Invis and Ultravision every couple of minutes is much less painful than redoing that C2 (or much worse, KEI) and Haste... not to mention the poor Clerics and Shamen who are crying/canni'ing themselves into oblivion.<br>
<br>
That's about all I can think of at the moment.  As I said in the first post, flexibility is the key; if you can adapt quickly to changing circumstances, this will save your butt many more times (at least at the early raid level) than searching for that 'perfect' lineup or strategy will.  And when all else fails, remember the mantra of my cleric friend and I:  &quot;The damage you prevent may be far more important than the damage you do.&quot;<br>
<br>
Bleh, I'll shut up now.<br>
