<img src=http://24.116.131.151/tux.jpg height=120 width=120></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ukiradureatani.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kiradure Atani</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Boardfellow</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(3/4/02 3:19:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1893.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> What I can do on raids</span><hr size=1> Often overlooked is the prospect of Damage shields, which I find to be more viable in groups than raid situations since keeping agro on one person (read:  Mob only taking DS damage from one source) is critical in high end situations.<br>
<br>
Snare sometimes, but with rangers and other druids there's a dozen other sources for snaring the mob, Epic if the battle is long enough to merit it.<br>
<br>
Typically as a druid I find myself spot healing.  Importantly, I toss Chloroblasts at our poor enchanters when they need it, other casters that took the agro a little too soon... Depending on the situation I'll also keep an eye out for other tanks who've gone into berserker frenzies, ect.  I try to keep an eye on friends as well but sometimes its more important to keep the group enchanter/shaman alive than Spite =*(<br>
<br>
Aside from spot heals, I keep Fixation and Ro's Fiery in the lineup provided that fire debuffing is feasible, and if that works well and mana is up I'll nuke like hell.  <br>
<br>
That pretty much does it for druids, depending on how large scale the raid is and where agro is focused, DSing is good, debuffage is good and spot heals are probably most imprtant in my book. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/urolielkotn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>RolielKotN</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Veteran</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(3/4/02 4:05:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1893.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What I can do on raids</span><hr size=1> Kelraz, I'm pretty sure Niv's Melody of Preservation doesn't increase AC or ATK (well, not directly - since some str is given, your ATK will go up). I'll check when I log on tonight, but I'm nearly 99.9% sure of this. Doesn't make it a worthless song though, I sing it quite often, as it's regen effect (and the fact that it stacks with Cantata) makes it very worthwhile.<br>
<br>
Okay, now for what I think bards are good for on raids. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
1.) AE resists. Probably our most noticable benefit to raids, these songs kick ass. They give 105-ish to MR and CR/FR or DR/PR (depending on which song you use, and what kind of drums you have - non-magical drums would have it at 90, no drums would have it at 45).<br>
<br>
2.) Mana/hp/sta regeneration. AE or not, still a great song.<br>
<br>
3.) Resistance Debuffs. Occulsion of Sound debuffs 25 MR, CR, and FR, is unresistable, and requires a drum to be equipped. This is good for helping casters land nukes and slow, and if needed, helping your enchanter land their mez (I don't see bards working with chanters very often, we can help them out quite a bit). Also, if you're not 55+, you can use the Target Dots to debuff MR, FR, or CR, however you're usually singing something else.<br>
<br>
4.) Damage Shields. Bards can provide a more powerful damage shield than any other class (which doesn't matter - it all stacks anyways, I just like to brag about bards <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ). At level 58, with a Vox horn and a Singing Steel bracer, a bard can get a DS of 37, which stacks with other class's DS's as well. SS bracer = 9 pt DS, Psalm of Warmth/Cooling = 10 pt DS, and McVax's Berzerker Crescendo = 16 pt DS. With an epic (or amplifacation, I haven't tested it with that yet), you can add an 80% bonus to Psalm of Warmth/Cooling.<br>
<br>
5.) Damage absorption. Shield of Songs can be nice for longer fights. With a Lute of the Howler, I think it absorbs about 44 points of damage. Last night my guild fought a mob with a considerable amount of hp, so my group was setup like this: Me, lvl 58 bard, Moonrunner 60 war, Gnevic 60 cleric, Brenye 57 cleric, Jesslynn 55 cleric, and Zionna 53 cleric. I sang Cantata and 2 rounds of Shield of Songs. Cantata helped a lot with regen, and Shield of Songs absorbed some of the damage that Moonrunner was taking, and some of the damage that the clerics were taking by using mod rods (works with Cannibalize too).<br>
<br>
6.) Stackable haste. Battlecry/Warsong of the Vahshir (lvl 52 and 60, respectively) are absolutely wonderful songs. They stack with chanter/shaman haste, and our other songs. Great for melee-heavy groups.<br>
<br>
7.) Tanking! Erm, wait. Let the warriors do that, it makes 'em feel important. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
8.) Mana Sieve, /shrug. We can do it, it's not very powerful. I might sing this song if we're short on chanters for MS, or if I'm having trouble thinking of something else to sing. Since the lvl 57 int/wis debuff lowers total the total mana pool, it's nice to sing at the beginning of the fight. Even just one round of it will still effect the mob after it wears off, since the mob would need to regain the mana lost by it's int/wis debuff after it wore.<br>
<br>
9.) Charming. If the bard times their charm well, it's a nice tool for zones like Kael where mobs cannot be mezzed, but are still charmable. Even if a chanter is present, it *might* be worth it for the bard to charm so the chanter can keep their mana up for haste/clarity. Also, we can take a lot more of a beating than chanters can, and have a discipline for 15 seconds of auto-dodge if we're risking death.<br>
<br>
10.) Pulling. Yes, you heard me - pulling. While we're rarely the pulling choice, we often can be. Think of zones where you raid, and are possibly not KoS. Right now, I'm ally in Skyshrine. If I chose to hose that faction and raid there, I would make one hell of a puller. What's the trick? Charm. If you charm something and it's not KoS, it's buddies won't aggro on you since it's your pet. I could split one mob from twenty, I'd like to meet a monk capable of that. One thing that sucks though, is having it resisted. If that's the case, you obviously won't get a single pull. Also, a lot of zones have uncharmable mobs.<br>
<br>
11.) Group Divine Aura. I don't think this needs an explanation. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Kelraz, you sound knowledgable of our class, but I thought I'd give you my thoughts anyways. Good luck making your Raiding Guide, I'd like to see it when it's done. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><IMG SRC=http://www.tiannathomas.com/images/roliel3.gif>
